<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JAN 93 / UK Company News: Waterglade cuts debt to Bank of America
with asset sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WATERGLADE International Holdings has agreed a financial restructuring that
involves Bank of America, its largest bank, taking control of the property
company's biggest asset.
In return for Waterglade's shopping complex in Havant, Hampshire, which has
a book value of Pounds 16.2m, Bank of America has extinguished all but
Pounds 1.7m of debt. This balance will be paid over a two-year period.
Mr David Cunningham, chairman, said the deal was crucial to the rescue. The
company 'was heading for the iceberg and now there is a good chance it can
be stabilised,' he said.
As a result of the deal, the group's debt falls from Pounds 41.49m to Pounds
25.3m.
Net assets at the last balance sheet date were Pounds 3.3m and the group
yesterday reported an attributable loss of Pounds 765,000 in the six months
to September 30.
Mr Cunningham said the full market value was not wholly reflected in the
books as all the properties had been moved into current assets and were held
at cost.
Waterglade will now embark upon a capital reorganisation.
The chairman said debts with some other banks are still to be tidied up. The
company would then provide a platform for the building of stakes in other
property companies that are in difficulty.
Waterglade's remaining assets include property in London and Wales with a
book value of Pounds 27m and rent role currently at Pounds 1.9m.
The interim pre-tax deficit was Pounds 954,000, compared with Pounds 3.33m
in 1991, and the loss per share worked through at 5.9p (12.6p).
</TEXT>
