FT  25 JAN 93 / International Company News: Bradesco rises 77% to Dollars
289m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BILL HINCHBERGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRADESCO, Brazil's largest private bank, posted profits of Dollars 289m for
1992, a 77 per cent increase over 1991.
The improvement was partly due to a 25 per cent reduction in provisions for
bad debts to Dollars 116m for the year.
Loan operations accounted for 28 per cent of the results while a substantial
proportion came from subsidiaries, mostly from Bradesco Seguros, the bank's
insurance unit.
'The Brazilian insurance market continued growing in 1992, and Bradesco is
the market leader,' explained Mr Alcides Lopes Tapias, vice-president.
The bank benefited from Brazil's increase in exports. It handled Dollars
6.4bn of exchange operations for shipments abroad, representing 16.7 per
cent of the market. The bank enjoyed a 25 per cent increase in this area.
Mr Tapias said Bradesco pushed ahead with cost cutting.
