<HEADLINE>
FT  25 JAN 93 / International Company News: ENI venture in Venezuela
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ENI, the Italian industrial group, and Petroleos de Venezuela, the
Venezuelan state oil group, have agreed to build a Dollars 360m methanol
plant in Venezuela, with Chemical Bank of the US and Banca Commerciale
Italiana of Italy providing part of the equity for the project.
The industrial partners and the participating banks yesterday signed a total
of Dollars 206m of debt financing facilities for the project. Under the
agreement, a total equity component of Dollars 142m for Supermetanol will be
provided, with Ecofuel and Pequiven each subscribing Dollars 49m, while
Chemical Bank and BCI will each subscribe Dollars 22m.
BCI and Chemical said the Dollars 22m equity component represents a
conversion of Venezuelan state debt which the banks had acquired through the
1989 restructuring of Venezuelan state debt.
The debt finance facilities also include a L145bn (Dollars 99m) export
credit facility, a Dollars 68.4m Euroloan facility, and a Dollars 47m term
financing provided by Corporacion Andina de Fomento.
The Supermetanol project has been set up by Ecofuel, a subsidiary of the ENI
group which manufactures MTBE (a high octane product), and Pequiven, a
wholly-owned subsidiary of the Venezuelan state oil group. The Supermetanol
plant is expected to have an annual capacity of 670,000 tonnes of methanol,
a component of MTBE.
</TEXT>
